very and virtue, but instead is caught up in intense first-person testimony on the psychology of desire. Unavailable in English for more than two centuries, Zayde reemerges here in Nicholas Paige’s accessible and vibrant translation as a worthy representative of a once popular genre and will be welcomed by readers of French literature and students of the European novelistic tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFrench literaturexTranslations into Englishx17th century. 0aFrench literaturey17th centuryvTranslations into English. 0aLove. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aiberian peninsula, medieval, christianity, islam, religion, spirituality, empire, borders, madame de lafayette, romance, novel, literature, suspense, sensation, lovers, nobility, aristocracy, shipwrecks, class, adventure, prophecy, fate, destiny, battles, war, military, cyprus, catalonia, jealousy, love, lust, desire, passion, sexuality, translation, french.1 aPaige, Nicholas D.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022646851840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226468440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226468440/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles